351
00:26:34.960 --> 00:26:36.830
And then he started doing calculations here.

352
00:26:36.830 --> 00:26:39.860
We rushed him, but he said he'd pay us.

353
00:26:39.860 --> 00:26:42.090
He took this place for a hotel.

354
00:26:42.690 --> 00:26:44.030
Can we go inside and talk to him?

355
00:26:44.030 --> 00:26:45.210
You can't.

356
00:26:45.210 --> 00:26:49.610
Just now he emphasized that you two have to wait for another four hours.

357
00:27:37.650 --> 00:27:40.260
It's been five hours.

358
00:27:40.260 --> 00:27:43.300
If he doesn't come out right now, I'll go in and unplug his computer.

359
00:27:44.940 --> 00:27:47.480
I'm asking you a question.

360
00:27:48.960 --> 00:27:50.070
Do it.

361
00:27:50.070 --> 00:27:51.480
Unplug it.

362
00:27:54.340 --> 00:27:57.590
If I unplug it, then he won't be able to figure it out, right?

363
00:27:58.610 --> 00:28:01.330
You're such a quick-tempered guy. Why do you care?

364
00:28:07.610 --> 00:28:09.160
Captain Shi, you guys may go in now.

365
00:28:09.160 --> 00:28:10.790
But that guy wants you to bring him some booze.

366
00:28:10.790 --> 00:28:13.510
Captain Shi, who is he? Why is he so cocky?

367
00:28:13.510 --> 00:28:15.490
Booze? Good.

368
00:28:15.490 --> 00:28:19.030
Him wanting booze is good news. It means he made a breakthrough.

369
00:28:23.410 --> 00:28:24.790
Tell me.

370
00:28:24.790 --> 00:28:28.840
Staying at home is so comfortable. Why did you come here?

371
00:28:30.200 --> 00:28:33.410
Long story.

372
00:28:34.350 --> 00:28:36.160
How about we do some celebrating first?

373
00:28:36.160 --> 00:28:39.740
Don't. If you do that, we won't be able to talk until tomorrow.

374
00:28:40.390 --> 00:28:41.510
Come on. Tell us.

375
00:28:41.510 --> 00:28:45.460
Tell us how many steps have you taken?

376
00:28:49.930 --> 00:28:52.650
I've built a model.

377
00:28:52.650 --> 00:28:56.410
Can the model solve the Three-Body problem?

378
00:28:57.610 --> 00:29:00.240
That needs verifying.

379
00:29:00.240 --> 00:29:02.640
This is such a crucial juncture.

380
00:29:02.640 --> 00:29:06.110
Did you specially come to the Public Security Bureau to finish it?

381
00:29:06.880 --> 00:29:09.210
Because someone threatened me.

382
00:29:09.210 --> 00:29:11.410
This is the safest place.

383
00:29:13.310 --> 00:29:15.650
Threatened you?

384
00:29:15.650 --> 00:29:19.870
- Who? 
 - If I'm to tell you that,

385
00:29:19.870 --> 00:29:23.050
I'll have to start from the beginning.

386
00:29:23.050 --> 00:29:26.640
Today I feel a bit weary.

387
00:29:26.640 --> 00:29:29.720
If you guys really want to hear it,

388
00:29:29.720 --> 00:29:32.890
I might need to shift into a comfortable position and take my time.

389
00:29:32.890 --> 00:29:35.210
Go ahead. Find yourself a comfortable position.

390
00:29:35.210 --> 00:29:36.160
Tell us.

391
00:29:36.160 --> 00:29:38.080
Sorry.

392
00:29:56.820 --> 00:30:00.160
It all started when I was in high school.

393
00:30:00.160 --> 00:30:02.640
No, no, no. Skip the high school part.

394
00:30:02.640 --> 00:30:04.070
High school is way off-topic.

395
00:30:04.070 --> 00:30:05.350
No.

396
00:30:05.350 --> 00:30:07.020
If I don't go off-topic,

397
00:30:07.020 --> 00:30:09.510
I'm afraid you guys won't be able to understand.

398
00:30:10.130 --> 00:30:12.000
Well, go ahead.

399
00:30:16.680 --> 00:30:20.880
It all started when I was in high school.

400
00:30:21.560 --> 00:30:26.840
<i>[The number of arrays]</i>

401
00:30:30.200 --> 00:30:32.020
<i>You have one hour.</i>

402
00:30:32.020 --> 00:30:33.780
<i>Can you work it out?</i>

403
00:30:47.440 --> 00:30:52.100
<i>[Minimum]</i>

404
00:31:06.240 --> 00:31:08.030
<i>And the derivation process?</i>

405
00:31:08.030 --> 00:31:10.060
<i>The derivation processâ€¦</i>

406
00:31:10.060 --> 00:31:11.680
<i>I don't know.</i>

407
00:31:14.400 --> 00:31:16.890
<i>You deduced too fast.</i>

408
00:31:16.890 --> 00:31:19.160
<i>And you did it instinctively.</i>

409
00:31:19.160 --> 00:31:22.400
<i>So even you yourself cannot perceive it.</i>

410
00:31:22.400 --> 00:31:28.370
<i>Just like it's difficult for people to explain how they deduce two plus two is four.</i>

411
00:31:29.780 --> 00:31:31.760
<i>What are numbers in your eyes?</i>

412
00:31:32.440 --> 00:31:34.590
<i>Solid figures.</i>

413
00:31:34.590 --> 00:31:36.000
<i>What about geometric shapes?</i>

414
00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:38.150
<i>They're numbers.</i>

415
00:31:38.150 --> 00:31:40.620
<i>You have a mathematical talent.</i>

416
00:31:42.060 --> 00:31:43.650
<i>Butâ€¦</i>

417
00:31:44.650 --> 00:31:49.550
<i>But people like you will never appreciate your talents.</i>

418
00:31:53.100 --> 00:31:55.260
My teacher was right.

419
00:31:55.260 --> 00:31:57.960
I don't know how to appreciate myself.

420
00:31:58.900 --> 00:32:01.648
I was shiftless when I was an undergraduate, graduate, and doctor.  
 <i>[Legend of the Flying Fox]</i>

421
00:32:01.648 --> 00:32:04.400
Surprisingly, I managed to muddle through.

422
00:32:04.400 --> 00:32:08.500
Afterward I became a college teacher, but still couldn't pull myself together.

423
00:32:08.500 --> 00:32:11.400
I wrote the words "easy to prove" on the blackboard,

424
00:32:11.400 --> 00:32:15.240
but my students couldn't figure it out no matter how hard they tried.

425
00:32:15.240 --> 00:32:18.440
We waited for you for almost five hours

426
00:32:18.440 --> 00:32:22.500
not to hear you brag to us or tell us you're a genius.

427
00:32:22.500 --> 00:32:23.790
You're wrong.

428
00:32:23.790 --> 00:32:25.860
I'm no genius.

429
00:32:27.590 --> 00:32:29.790
I'm a good-for-nothing.

430
00:32:29.790 --> 00:32:34.160
Except for maths, I can't do anything properly.

431
00:32:34.160 --> 00:32:36.210
My life's getting worse and worse.

432
00:32:36.210 --> 00:32:39.170
Suddenly, one day, I got tired of all that,

433
00:32:39.170 --> 00:32:42.780
so I packed some stuff and went to a temple.

434
00:32:42.780 --> 00:32:44.860
You became a Buddhist monk?

435
00:32:44.860 --> 00:32:46.820
Weren't you married?

436
00:32:46.820 --> 00:32:48.260
You're wrong again.

437
00:32:48.260 --> 00:32:50.380
I couldn't be bothered to become a monk.

438
00:32:50.380 --> 00:32:54.260
I just wanted a quiet place where I could blow off some steam.

439
00:32:54.260 --> 00:32:56.370
An old friend of my father's lived there.

440
00:32:56.370 --> 00:32:59.830
He was very knowledgeable, but when he got old, he became a monk.

441
00:32:59.830 --> 00:33:02.380
According to my father,

442
00:33:02.380 --> 00:33:04.920
people like him

443
00:33:06.920 --> 00:33:09.480
had no other choice.

444
00:33:34.480 --> 00:33:36.780
<i>No. I'm sorry.</i>

445
00:33:51.160 --> 00:33:53.410
<i>Stop pretending.</i>

446
00:33:55.020 --> 00:33:57.610
<i>Is this necessary?</i>

447
00:33:57.610 --> 00:33:59.680
<i>I'm trying to understand Buddhism.</i>

448
00:33:59.680 --> 00:34:02.650
<i>Talking about Buddhism with a guy like you?</i>

449
00:34:02.650 --> 00:34:04.030
<i>That's pointless.</i>

450
00:34:04.030 --> 00:34:05.740
<i>Come with me.</i>

451
00:34:23.400 --> 00:34:25.590
You may live here.

452
00:34:37.010 --> 00:34:39.800
Actually, I don't care where I live.

453
00:34:39.800 --> 00:34:43.670
I just want to find a quiet place

454
00:34:43.670 --> 00:34:46.640
to fiddle around for the rest of my life.

455
00:34:48.840 --> 00:34:50.590
This place is not quiet.

456
00:34:50.590 --> 00:34:52.760
There are many people coming and going.

457
00:34:52.760 --> 00:34:55.000
The safest hideout is the crowd.

458
00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:59.290
If you want quietness, you have to empty yourself.

459
00:35:06.860 --> 00:35:08.380
Flush.

460
00:35:17.480 --> 00:35:19.760
How can I make myself emptier?

461
00:35:19.760 --> 00:35:22.900
Fame and wealth are less than nothing to me.

462
00:35:22.900 --> 00:35:24.550
Come over here.

463
00:35:25.190 --> 00:35:27.190
Come here.

464
00:35:29.840 --> 00:35:31.190
Look.

465
00:35:31.190 --> 00:35:33.150
What is this?

466
00:35:33.150 --> 00:35:34.700
Isn't it just a radio?

467
00:35:34.700 --> 00:35:37.480
- May I ask why it doesn't have an antenna?
- You geek.

468
00:35:37.480 --> 00:35:39.230
It's Bluetooth-enabled.

469
00:35:39.230 --> 00:35:41.030
Bluetooth?

470
00:36:06.300 --> 00:36:07.920
Is this a radio?

471
00:36:07.920 --> 00:36:10.220
This is an amplifier.

472
00:36:14.030 --> 00:36:15.280
Is this a radio?

473
00:36:15.280 --> 00:36:17.780
This is a transistor.

474
00:36:19.670 --> 00:36:22.110
This is a capacitor.

475
00:36:22.110 --> 00:36:24.130
Where's the radio?

476
00:36:32.230 --> 00:36:32.860
Gone.

477
00:36:32.860 --> 00:36:39.070
So radio is just a temporary pseudonym we gave these components.

478
00:36:39.070 --> 00:36:43.550
If you dismantle it in your mind, it'll cease to exist.

479
00:36:43.550 --> 00:36:47.700
Therefore, radio is not a permanent entity.

480
00:36:47.700 --> 00:36:52.590
These things can become a radio or a pile of components.

481
00:36:52.590 --> 00:36:56.030
This process is emptying.

482
00:36:57.480 --> 00:37:00.480
What does "Form is emptiness" means?

483
00:37:00.480 --> 00:37:06.920
If you're right, then form is only a process.

484
00:37:06.920 --> 00:37:11.200
Form means everything you can see.

485
00:37:12.710 --> 00:37:15.320
Emptiness is not nothingness.

486
00:37:15.320 --> 00:37:21.630
You need to fill yourself with emptiness.

487
00:37:46.740 --> 00:37:49.630
I couldn't sleep that night,

488
00:37:49.630 --> 00:37:54.000
so I kept pondering over Professor Han's remark.

489
00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:57.260
I never thought the never-never land
would be so uncomfortable.

490
00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:01.650
My sheets were very damp due to the mountain mist.

491
00:38:01.650 --> 00:38:04.670
And the bed was very hard.

492
00:38:04.670 --> 00:38:07.130
It made it difficult for me to sleep.

493
00:38:07.130 --> 00:38:13.830
To get to sleep, I tried doing as Professor Han said.

494
00:38:16.760 --> 00:38:20.950
Filling myself with emptiness.

495
00:38:26.510 --> 00:38:28.450
Can you guys understand?

496
00:38:30.900 --> 00:38:32.830
Go on.

497
00:39:20.230 --> 00:39:24.450
In my mind, I created the first "emptiness".

498
00:39:25.550 --> 00:39:28.260
It's a boundless space.

499
00:39:28.800 --> 00:39:34.400
There's nothing in it, not even light.

500
00:39:34.400 --> 00:39:36.320
Absolutely empty.

501
00:39:38.710 --> 00:39:45.000
Soon I realized that the empty universe couldn't calm me down.

502
00:39:46.190 --> 00:39:50.800
Being in there made me feel inexplicably anxious.

503
00:39:50.800 --> 00:39:55.250
Like someone drowning in a river who's trying to grab something within reach.

504
00:39:55.250 --> 00:39:57.070
So

505
00:39:59.190 --> 00:40:03.000
I created a sphere for myself

506
00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:05.590
in the infinite space.

507
00:40:10.440 --> 00:40:14.670
That was a sphere with mass, not big.

508
00:40:19.760 --> 00:40:22.490
But it didn't make me feel better.

509
00:40:23.180 --> 00:40:25.840
The sphere was floating in the center of the space.

510
00:40:25.840 --> 00:40:27.840
Nothing in the universe was exerting any forces on it,

511
00:40:27.840 --> 00:40:30.420
and there was nothing for it to exert forces on either.

512
00:40:31.150 --> 00:40:33.480
It just floated in there.

513
00:40:33.480 --> 00:40:38.230
It would never move, or change in any way.

514
00:40:39.280 --> 00:40:42.660
That's the most perfect interpretation of death.

515
00:40:43.670 --> 00:40:48.500
Therefore, I created another sphere,

